%I A394501 #77 Jul 22 2026 18:52:37
%S A394501 2,4,4,8,12,19,26,40,50,73,88,122,142,190,217,283,317,403,448,556,612,
%T A394501 747,816,984,1066,1269,1370,1610,1730,2014,2155,2491,2653,3043,3234,
%U A394501 3680,3900,4411,4662,5248,5530,6193,6516,7258,7622,8454,8861,9795,10245,11283
%N A394501 Number of reachable belief states for one hunter and an invisible rabbit on the n-vertex path graph.
%C A394501 A hunter wants to shoot a rabbit that is hiding behind one of n bushes in a row. The hunter selects one of the bushes and shoots at it. If the rabbit is behind the selected bush, the hunter wins. Otherwise, the rabbit jumps invisibly to an adjacent bush, and the hunter must guess again. The sequence counts sets of possible locations for the rabbit consistent with survival so far.
%C A394501 Let P_n denote the n-vertex path graph with vertex set V. Then a(n) is the cardinality of the smallest family of subsets of V that contains V and is closed under the transitions A -> N(A \ {v}) for all v in V, where N(S) denotes the open neighborhood of S in P_n.
%C A394501 a(n) is a quasipolynomial of degree 4 and period 8 for n >= 4.
%H A394501 T. V. Abramovskaya, F. V. Fomin, P. A. Golovach, and M. Pilipczuk, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ejc.2015.08.002">How to Hunt an Invisible Rabbit on a Graph</a>, European Journal of Combinatorics 52 (2016): 12-26.
%H A394501 Alex Bellos, <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/science/2017/jul/03/can-you-solve-it-are-you-smarter-than-a-cat">Can you solve it? Are you smarter than a cat?</a>, The Guardian, Jul 3 2017.
%H A394501 J. R. Britnell and M. Wildon, <a href="https://doi.org/10.37236/2296">Finding a princess in a palace: A pursuit-evasion problem</a>, The Electronic Journal of Combinatorics, 20(1), #P25, 2013.
%H A394501 J. Haslegrave, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.disc.2013.09.004">An evasion game on a graph</a>, Discrete Mathematics 314 (2014): 1-5.
%H A394501 David Radcliffe, <a href="https://radcliffe.dev/demos/invisible-rabbit.html">Invisible Rabbit</a>, an interactive demo, 2026.
%H A394501 Presh Talwalkar, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yZyx9gHhRXM">How To Solve The Hiding Cat Puzzle - Microsoft Interview Riddle</a>, YouTube video, 2017.
%H A394501 <a href="/index/Rec#order_21">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (1,2,-2,-1,1,0,0,2,-2,-4,4,2,-2,0,0,-1,1,2,-2,-1,1).
%F A394501 a(n) = a(n-1) + 2*a(n-2) - 2*a(n-3) - a(n-4) + a(n-5) + 2*a(n-8) - 2*a(n-9) - 4*a(n-10) + 4*a(n-11) + 2*a(n-12) - 2*a(n-13) - a(n-16) + a(n-17) + 2*a(n-18) - 2*a(n-19) - a(n-20) + a(n-21) for n >= 25.
%F A394501 a(n) = 5*a(n-8) - 10*a(n-16) + 10*a(n-24) - 5*a(n-32) + a(n-40) for n >= 44.
%F A394501 a(n) ~ n^4/1024.
%F A394501 G.f.: (2*x + 2*x^2 - 4*x^3 + 6*x^5 + x^6 - x^7 + 4*x^8 - 4*x^9 - 2*x^10 + 10*x^11 + 2*x^12 - 12*x^13 + x^14 + 4*x^15 - 4*x^16 + 2*x^17 - 4*x^19 - 2*x^20 + 6*x^21 - 3*x^23 + 2*x^24) / ((1-x)*(1-x^2)^2*(1-x^8)^2).
%F A394501 Let n = 8*m + r, where m >= 0 and 0 <= r <= 7. For n >= 4, a(n) =
%F A394501  4*m^4   + 18*m^3 + 21*m^2  - 6*m   + 3        if r = 0,
%F A394501  (12*m^4 + 58*m^3 + 75*m^2  - 10*m  + 15) / 3  if r = 1,
%F A394501  4*m^4   + 22*m^3 + 36*m^2  + 8*m   + 3        if r = 2,
%F A394501  (12*m^4 + 70*m^3 + 123*m^2 + 41*m  + 18) / 3  if r = 3,
%F A394501  4*m^4   + 26*m^3 + 54*m^2  + 30*m  + 8        if r = 4,
%F A394501  (12*m^4 + 82*m^3 + 180*m^2 + 116*m + 36) / 3  if r = 5,
%F A394501  4*m^4   + 30*m^3 + 75*m^2  + 62*m  + 19       if r = 6, and
%F A394501  (12*m^4 + 94*m^3 + 246*m^2 + 221*m + 78) / 3  if r = 7.
%e A394501 For n = 3, the four reachable states are {1, 2, 3}, {1, 3}, {2}, and {}. For example, successive shots at bushes 2, 1, 2, 2 produce the belief states {1, 2, 3} --> {2} --> {1, 3} --> {2} --> {}.
%o A394501 (Python)
%o A394501 def A394501(n):
%o A394501     mask = (1 << n) - 1
%o A394501     seen = {mask}
%o A394501     queue = [mask]
%o A394501     while queue:
%o A394501         state = queue.pop()
%o A394501         for k in range(n):
%o A394501             survivors = state & ~(1 << k)
%o A394501             new_state = ((survivors >> 1) | (survivors << 1)) & mask
%o A394501             if new_state not in seen:
%o A394501                 seen.add(new_state)
%o A394501                 queue.append(new_state)
%o A394501     return len(seen)
%K A394501 nonn,easy,new
%O A394501 1,1
%A A394501 _David Radcliffe_, Jul 16 2026
